Especially paying $30, to be blinded through entire songs. Also, the vocals were hard to understand, a little muddy, not crisp. I heard that from another patron as well. overal_event_expression: The Paperboys concert was amazing.  I have seen them twice before in Leavenworth and I have all of their albums.  The talent of the band is unbelievable.  However, I was very disappointed with the sound system. For one thing, it was just way too loud for the size of the venue.  I was in the sixth row and my friends and I felt like we were being blasted with sound.  Even more frustrating was that the mix for the vocals seemed way off. We could hardly hear what Tom was singing. It sounded like he was under 10 feet of water. It probably sounded ok in the balcony but it was very muddy in the front rows.  The sad thing is that the acoustics are very good in the theatre.  I sing with the Choral Society and we have sung there several times. There is no need to blast the music like they are in a stadium.  Anyway, we still enjoyed the show, but were disappointed with the sound system. Please bring them back and turn down the amps! :) Thanks!

overal_event_expression: Mike Wylie was very engaging. His genuine joy in interacting with the audience was unsurpassed. Regardless of the small audience size, he entertained, engaged, and performed with the greatest interests. Sound was an issue for both the announcer and actor as was conversation during the performance. It sounded like one of the entry doors was left open and what was meant to be a private conversation was now public. A friend had heard about his performance from a grade school grandchild who was impressed with his message and performance. The children, whom he selected to interact on stage were delighted to be chosen. His Q & A after was engaging and encouraged those free thinking artisans in the audience to continue to see this gift as valuable, as he relayed his interest in people watching and mimicing voices/body language as a child, which led to his performance career.  We are glad to hear that he will be returning next year.
feeback_suggestion: Perhaps complimentary tickets at the school performances, which would be coordinated through school office personnel would be another incentive for families to attend.

overal_event_expression: I found out through this event through Spotify! My husband and I are big fans of Luca and Thu Le and were super excited to see that they would be performing in Walla Walla. We were thrilled with the value, performance, and lighting. The staff were incredibly helpful and friendly. There were a couple of mishaps with the sound, but they were handled well and didn't detract from the show at all. Overall, we were incredibly impressed and are looking forward to visiting again in the future, especially if International Guitar Night returns. No other suggestions except to thank everyone who worked hard to put on an incredible evening. From the ushers, the box office staff, the refreshment staff, greeters, sound and lighting, stage managers, and all of the other traditionally unseen jobs: you are phenomenal and should be proud of putting on one of the best events I've ever been to! Thank you for a wonderful and memorable night.

overal_event_expression: There were some relatively minor issues with the sound and lighting.  A couple of times, sound-surging feedback got pretty loud; fortunately, it was short-lived.  Then, there was a glimmering or bright glare strobing off one of the guitars due to the lighting angle.  It was projected into the crowd, and some of us couldn't look at the stage as a result.  Again, it didn't last long and was tolerable.  The majority of the show was fantastic.  The collaborative and individual guitar playing ranged from mesmerizing to rock wake up!
feeback_suggestion: The guitarists were so generous with their collaborations.  Not only did they spotlight each other, but they engaged in well-meaning competition which magnified their own talents as well.  The concept of combining musical artists from different countries is an extraordinary way to learn about the sounds of other cultures.  Combining players from Vietnam, Italy, Brazil and Australia turned out a remarkable, eclectic, harmonic and savory blending of genres.  VIBA (the first letter of each country) Las Vegas, baby!  Come back.

overal_event_expression: We have heard the group in past years. We were not pleased with our seats. As soon as I heard about the dates I called in and asked for best available. We were give n seats that were stage right that were BEHIND the group. Frequently the violin player turned her head so we could see her whole face, but we rarely saw more than a profile of the lead singer. The sound was fine because we didn't need the mics to hear everything, couldn't really tell you whether the lighting was good or not, we couldn't see. The value was not there. I have back and balance issues so sitting on folding chairs when I expected a "theatre" type chair was unacceptable. I should have been warned where the seats were and what I would be sitting on before I purchased my tickets. Also, why didn't your ushers have a diagram of the theatre to help people find their seats, we were told THREE or FOUR times where to sit before we found our folding chairs.
feeback_suggestion: Gerald Friesen, 509-540-1464. The lady we finally had that helped us find our seats was great, she offered to let me get up and walk around during the show and she knew exactly where our seats were, she did have a name tag on that looked like she was someone important. If more of your workers were like her there would be less people people  like me that had to stand and wait while an usher went and got instructions.....that turned out to be WRONG. I had to use the rest room  twice because it took so long to find my folding chair. At least buy 12 to 18 folding chairs that are comfortable to sit on and give these things to someone who deals in SCRAP metal.

overal_event_expression: Headliner was fogged in and didn't make it.  Two replacements.  Not too bad.  The sub-replacement - the self proclaimed gay anesthesiologist - may have been a bit much for Walla Walla.   His gay jokes seemed more like therapy; but when he moved on to his Jewish and other material he was funny.  I didn't mind the gay jokes, but the material seemed a bit forced.  The main replacement started off slowly, but got rolling and was pretty good.  He was particularly good at weaving the audience reactions (or lack of reactions) into his routine.  The best I've seen at the PHT is still Kermit Apio - he made my sides hurt from laughing so hard.
feeback_suggestion: Bring back Kermit Apio.

overal_event_expression: I am sorry to say but the sound was horrible. I have good hearing and so would have thought it was just the film itself but even the previews were unintelligible. My seat was extremely uncomfortable as well. No cushion, not to mention how narrow they are. At twice the price of the movie theater I am sorry to say I won’t be choosing to see more films at GESA.
feeback_suggestion: Then there was the film itself.  Besides being unintelligible most of the time, the dialogue was boring, the story was very scattered. Maybe it was trying to cover too many issues? Immigrants struggles, race, income disparity, gentrification, disregard and disrespect for the beauty of diverse cultures and communities…. I feel the messages were lost in too much mundane interactions. What has happened to the culture of neighborhoods in Seattle, which is unfortunately true all over the US, was lost in the scattered script. We sat through 1 1/2 hours and left.

overal_event_expression:
Sadly this was the first disappointing event we attended at GPHT. The event was promoted on social media as DINNER with food provided from multiple local purveyors. Instead Marcus Whitman was the only provider of eats and they were finger food appetizers. We saved our appetites for this event and were very hungry by the time the event ended. The appetizers were good but not great. For the price we paid, I would have expected two comp glasses of wine per attendee, especially given the smallish size of the pours.

The film sound was muffled in the balcony for us. Also given the accents of the people featured in the films, having captions displayed would have been very helpful. Also good for people with less than perfect hearing. The films felt longer than they needed to be and the subject matter could have more varied. The non-documentary film was entertaining. 
The event didn't deliver the value relative to the cost of the tickets. Highly unlikely we will attend the Film Feast if it returns next year.
Wish I had more positive feedback as this was the first disappointing event especially compared to the wonderful programming we've attended in the past.
feeback_suggestion: Captions for movies. No need to respond but happy to answer questions: stevekilisky@gmail.com

overal_event_expression: Outstanding! It's fun to have some of the best players in the world here in Walla Walla!
feeback_suggestion: I have been to this show for the last two years, and I must say, the 2024 performance felt like it had a much higher energy level. I am sure that the players are given some freedom to play whatever they want in those opening solos, but last night all four started with slow pieces, a couple of which were introduced with sort of sad, tragic anecdotes about the origin of the piece. Way to get the crowd into it! :) I know this is only one show and now they're gone, and I'm not sure whether there is a show manager or anyone in place who might be able to put some thought into the makeup of the show, but even a slight lean toward the order of pieces and setting up the crowd would help. I know in 2024 , the Italian gentleman came out first and blew the roof off from the first note, which set the tone for the whole performance. This comment has nothing to do with ability to play the guitar. They are all incredible.   But song choice matters. :)

I think if the theatre did a better job promoting it as fun, interactive, and very moving, more people would have bought tickets. In walla walla, you cannot just put a picture of a Black man on a poster and think this population will be interested. They need to know that it will be fun and not just a “scary learning experience.” We are almost there, but still need help encouraging folks. I do hope he comes back next year, because our community deserves the experience. I, for sure, will be buying tickets.

overal_event_expression: Not sure that it's avoidable, but the spotlight at times reflected right off the instruments and into members of the audience's eyes.  In spite of that little distraction, the experience was incredible.  Have been to a couple of these before, and they are always delightful.  The whole synergy of bringing nations together--and particularly, during this tumultuous political moment--makes it even more poignant than ever to continue encouraging the unification of all people through music. overal_event_expression: Excellent selection of an interesting movie, well produced.  Both sound quality and projection quality were good.  Movies like this are of high value to the community in that they are unlikely to appear in for profit cinemas that need to screen a show multiple times.
feeback_suggestion:
I would like to see more movies at Gesa.  It’s a good venue for “arty” or even foreign films.  However, those films require a first class marketing program which I don’t think Gesa has yet managed to accomplish.  Looking at the list of where we might hear of these films, there doesn’t seem to be any outlet targeting college students at Whitman or Whitman’s arts/drama/music departments.  There are documentaries  (such as “giants Rising”) that would be of interest to younger people if the marketing informs them effectively and in advance.  At the screening, there were movies previewed that I was unaware of (not in the Gesa brochure that was handed out).  There has been Quest classes on movies but I don’t think those potential audiences have been targeted.  
I would also be interested in seeing Gesa explore subscribing to NTLive programming.  That might be a partnership with the colleges/university offering a student discount price.  Please look into NTLive (National Theater of London productions that are filmed on the final night of performances that are at times better than the actual show — I saw a live performance and later the NTLive film of the live production: the camera angles gave much better reading of the actors than seeing it live.). I highly recommend nearly all of their productions.

overal_event_expression: Loved this film--and the title was on point:  Holy Frit! indeed.  It encompassed captivating images; sound was just right; value was increased by the education which I feel I received watching the process of how to create stained/fused glass.  Such a journey for the artist, the production crews--glass makers, installers and camera manipulators, plus the courage it took to take on such an enormous endeavor.  The gigantic risks taken and the expenses incurred--constantly having to evolve was a great lesson for us all.
feeback_suggestion: This was one of the most memorable films I've seen at the Powerhouse.  Full of fun, humor, challenge, beauty, collaboration, glass artistry and more--with the ultimate result.  This film hooked me on researching the largest commissioned stained-glass project in the world (at the time) because it made me want to know more.  What an incredible feat to have considered, accepted and produced.  When I saw the eyes of Jesus (I'm not particularly religious.), it touched me in a deeply spiritual way from an artistic perspective.

So a few more of those could be the bread and butter of entertainment.at Gesa.  Would also welcome more jazz and blues bands and perhaps some modern dance routines.  Also like the rhythm and sounds of bongo drums, calypso or steel drums.

So a few more of those could be the bread and butter of entertainment.at Gesa.  Would also welcome more jazz and blues bands and perhaps some modern dance routines.  Also like the rhythm and sounds of bongo drums, calypso or steel drums.
combined_text: As Ceasar mentioned, there was a slight humming sound during a small portion of the performance; however, it wasn't that bad and was short-lived--at least from an audience perspective.  As a Nat King Cole fan, was pleased that he sang "Unforgettable" as one of his selections.  His accompanying pianist, Mark, was complementary and complimentary (both meanings).  Hope they both return to the Powerhouse.  The event was well-timed with Black History month, so thematic shows might be well-received. overal_event_expression: As always, the volunteers are particularly helpful, friendly and knowledgeable.  With this intimate venue, the quality of the lighting and sound (good volume) was appropriate.  Even with a small number of attendees, the value of such films does not lose its importance.  After all, just one person can start a ripple.  Well done.  Keep it up!
feeback_suggestion: Despite being Yiddish-impaired, my brain was connecting synapses at random and inter-communicating in an uncommon way.  The richness of the films allowed me to experience different levels of thought almost like a set of never-ending, falling dominoes.  The interviews (e.g., Sean Wainstein/Demon Box) shed new light on what the films delivered.  It became more than the sum of dark and light or the holocaust and survivorship--developing into an all-encompassing life and love of mankind thereafter.  That we’re all present in this “middle” of our lives because we’re not at the hour of our birth and not yet dead, was very powerful and thought-provoking.

overal_event_expression: Fabulous production that highlighted exceptional talent and creative ingenuity.  The production was excellent from start to finish.  Also, the chance to meet the members of the production after the show added to the enjoyment of the evening.  They are to be complimented for giving their time and interest in our community.  In conversation, it appeared that they did not know the history of the Power House Theatre and were notably impressed when mentioned.  This should be a given when prospective events and performers are being solicited to perform at the Theatre.  Indeed, our evening was special and well worth the price of admission.
feeback_suggestion: Would like to see the pre-show lobby amenities supported to a larger extent.  Would hope it could inspire 'meet and greet', good conversation and the opportunity to meet folks from the community.  Would like to suggest that the refreshments offered, particularly the wines, be priced more reasonably and/or a standard pour of 6 ounces be offered (not 5 oz.).  If the refreshments were more reasonably priced and also advertised with an event, this might help to encourage folks to come a little early and enjoy.

overal_event_expression: Most of the clips were of good quality in terms of production, but some were much softer than the rest and were difficult to hear (for example the first clip). I am not hard of hearing.
feeback_suggestion: Please post more information about the content of such collections; that would’ve tipped me off that this wasn’t the kind of show we wanted to see. My mother and I were expecting light-hearted, cheerful, heartwarming holiday fare—as per the title—and found it to be anything but that. Did anyone view it before deciding to show it at GESA? I’m not offended by moderate profanity in most settings (ok, the last clip was kinda funny), but for a *Christmas* collection this was an awful choice. It was dark, profane, disturbing and utterly unsuitable. One clip could only be called a horror short, I don’t care that they tried to be humorous with spurting green blood instead of red. The family in front of us, with three older teenagers, got up and left about ten minutes in. We rode it out hoping it would get better, and afterwards my mild, uncomplaining 83 yo mother simply said, “Well I hope you didn’t pay too much for that.”

overal_event_expression: Sound was great!! Couldn’t understand the smoke effect in the room, and I thought the lighting on Mike could’ve been better. However, overall, it was a great show!!! I was deeply touched at how vulnerable Mike allowed himself to become when telling his Walla Walla story. I feel like I have just, been to some kind of a Sacred service!! Good for him! Both my husband and I feel honored to have witnessed his processing of that story and still made us laugh. A great comedian and storyteller for sure.

source_of_hearing: Email, Gesa Power House Theatre website (www.phtww.org)
overal_event_expression: I attended the 9pm show, which was pushed back because of the earlier one running late. I really appreciated the venue staff clearly communicating the delay and making sure everyone knew what was going on. The sound was very clear but if I am totally honest it was at the lower end of audible. There was an obnoxious patron behind me who kept talking and as soon as she opened her mouth I pretty much couldn't hear Mike. I was in row LAA for what it's worth, so off to the side. I'm sure that made a difference.
feeback_suggestion: I would really appreciate venue staff circulating behind rows or along the sides and reminding disruptive audience members to keep it down. I've seen two comedy shows at the Powerhouse and my experience at both of them was negatively affected by other audience members who were clearly drunk and couldn't keep their mouths shut.

overal_event_expression:
The ushers were fantastic for the Mike Birbiglia show on Wednesday, January 24, 2024.    We were especially impressed at how a young woman came outside to give us "will call" tickets so as to not cause congestion before the show.  Very smart.  The crowding around the drinks bar created awkwardness.  Coziness was trumped by sluggish crowdedness.
       The lounge where we waited was just ok.  The lighting was good for the show.  The "fog" before the show impeded vision a bit.   Birbiglia himself was wonderful and very personable, and we hope you bring him back.

overal_event_expression: As usual, the lighting & sound were wonderful.  Much of the value is measured in the experience.  Sometimes, it's worth a little extra money to entice quality entertainment.  If the time spent brings forth something memorable, it's certain to allure people back to the theatre.  After 19 years, Mike Birbiglia returns to cathartically share his tragic incident at the Walla Walla La Quinta.  However, the ultimate outcome results in identifying his sleep disorder and putting him on a more acceptable life track.  Amazing story!
feeback_suggestion: All good.  Despite the event delay, it was carried off rather smoothly.  All volunteers were working very hard to keep attendees content.  Note that good people tend to come to events at the Gesa--no pushing, shoving or unruly types.  A margin of that is due to the friendly, industrious, service-oriented help.  Kudos to all worker bees; that's appreciated!  Wonder if there are any thoughts of bringing food trucks to the events?  I believe that option occurred in the past, but I don't know if it was considered successful or not.

overal_event_expression: Great performance!  Lighting and sound seemed fine.
feeback_suggestion:
I have noticed this at many concerts, not just the Birbiglia show.  
If there is one thing that could take the Powerhouse from good to great, it would be to allow seating of patrons one hour before show time. After a certain age, adults do not enjoy being mashed together like a techno club mosh pit or a cattle truck.  If lighting and sound checks need to be done before the show, I would humbly suggest that the technicians come in a half hour earlier.  If the performer gets too claustrophobic waiting an hour before the show, then we might consider updating the Green Room.
I have observed patrons becoming angry,  waiting  half an hour for the  doors to open. lve also observed the opposite.  The inevitable outcome of opening the house only 30 min before show time, is that you've trained patrons to arrive at the last minute and then they are being seated after the show  has begun.  This is incredibly distracting for the audience and  perhaps for the performer as  well.

We love coming a bit early to get parking and a glass of wine before the show. It makes the evening extra special. The ushers, greeters and wine servers were all so friendly and helpful!
feeback_suggestion: I would encourage you to maintain the high level of professional, family-friendly, and noncontroversial entertainment selections. Several of your recent/current performers are very offensive.

feeback_suggestion: As the Powerhouse Theater becomes more popular and makes enough money for improvements, please consider making changes to the facility. overal_event_expression: We thought the event was great! Sound and lighting were great, the comic was very enjoyable, and the tickets were reasonably priced. I thought the champagne toast was a very nice thought, but wasn't executed very well.
feeback_suggestion: This was our first time to the theater, and we really enjoyed the event! I realize that there may be very little that can be done about this, but my main comment for things to improve would be the congestion of the lobby before the show. I realize there are several things that need to take place (will call, ticket scanning, coat check, bar, etc.) in a relatively small space, but the crowding means people have to wait outside for a while so that they can squeeze between people to get through the lobby. Perhaps longer hours for the bar, moving will call, or something like that would be helpful for reducing congestion. That said, the staff were all very friendly, welcoming, and helpful!

overal_event_expression: Ticket prices were high for what it was...a good show but I had heard a good amount of the material previously on his posted videos...would have been nice to have more new material--especially for the new year-since it was advertised as a NYE special...was expecting new material not a lot of repeated/old jokes...
feeback_suggestion: Having a military/veteran discount available would be nice. Also, consistency in pricing on the website from the main page throughout the event pages...Many times it differs and is conflicting...ticket pricing info should be clear and concise at a minimum, especially at the prices being charged. These aren't discount/cheap tickets. Another little detail--When popcorn is served in the lobby - Make it fresh...Nothing says "We got you good" like paying $4 for a tiny bag of popcorn...only to find out it is STALE. That's just bad business and acting in bad faith

overal_event_expression:
Absolutely amazing.
The only thing that bothered us was the couple seated in front of us, we had G-9 and G- 10 seats. At intermission, the man, I certainly wouldn’t call him a gentleman, came us to us. I had complimented his female friend about her attire. He then said , my friend and I were too “chatty “ and could we not whisper or comment on the performance as it was distracting for him. We sat through the rest of the show in silence, while the audience continued to enjoy the wonderful display of talent we had mutually payed for. We were not by any means, outspoken or overbearing with making soft comments about  the amazing performance we were witnessing. I thank everyone that gives Walla Walla these amazing performances.
feeback_suggestion: Excellent staff, volunteers.

overal_event_expression: The person who manned the spotlight did an exceptional job of keeping up with all the rapid changes.  The sound was clear and at an appropriate volume making it a pleasant experience and bringing out the characteristics of each instrument:  marimba (xylophone), standard flute, Native American flute (one of my favorites; so haunting), saxophone(s), piano, standard (stick) drumming, long djembe(?) hand drumming along with extras like juggling, tap dancing, beat boxing and singing.  Very well done!
feeback_suggestion: The members of Collision of Rhythm were two extremely talented guys whose desire is clearly to teach and create a community-based experience.  Their enthusiasm shined on us all, and the audience participation was absolutely essential to a successful performance.  "We...we are made of music!"  To have a venue of inclusivity for younger and older generations alike is welcome.  The fast-moving tempo of the show kept it captivating.  Would love to see them return to the Gesa Powerhouse Theatre.  More power!

Their enthusiasm shined on us all, and the audience participation was absolutely essential to a successful performance.  "We...we are made of music!"  To have a venue of inclusivity for younger and older generations alike is welcome.  The fast-moving tempo of the show kept it captivating.  Would love to see them return to the Gesa Powerhouse Theatre.  More power!
combined_text: The person who manned the spotlight did an exceptional job of keeping up with all the rapid changes.  The sound was clear and at an appropriate volume making it a pleasant experience and bringing out the characteristics of each instrument:  marimba (xylophone), standard flute, Native American flute (one of my favorites; so haunting), saxophone(s), piano, standard (stick) drumming, long djembe(?) hand drumming along with extras like juggling, tap dancing, beat boxing and singing.  Very well done! The members of Collision of Rhythm were two extremely talented guys whose desire is clearly to teach and create a community-based experience.  Their enthusiasm shined on us all, and the audience participation was absolutely essential to a successful performance.  "We...we are made of music!"  To have a venue of inclusivity for younger and older generations alike is welcome.  The fast-moving tempo of the show kept it captivating.  Would love to see them return to the Gesa Powerhouse Theatre.  More power!

overal_event_expression: Loved the feel but was unimpressed with the house lights turning on just for the performers to "see our response." As a viewer I was taken out of the experience more than two times due to the house lights being on. Reference the russia tour of Billy Joel when he explains how much of an AV fail that is. When the house lights go down...keep em down. If the artist requests to have the audience a bit visible for the use of a practical part of the show that is planned, suggest other lighting sources from the stage such as the warmer lights used half way between the first act, to reflect on the audience. This venue is small enough to not have to worry about a disconnect from the performer to the audince, so I will stand by the fact that the house lights should stay down unless it is an emergency or intermission...or over lol.
feeback_suggestion: I would say that I would have loved for the security guard to have come down near the isle to reprimand the clown who had his flash on multiple times for pictures, instead of him being so near the stage and talking down to the front row. It was almost equally as distracting as the flashing light from the clown audience member. so if something like that happens to try to be stealthy before being tough. ninja not barbarian ;)

overal_event_expression:
Good show! Good production quality, except for one card trick for which the lighting was dimmed and I couldn’t see a thing he was doing. Thought the tickets were a bit overpriced; $40 seems more reasonable. 
Just as a side note, when I originally saw the photo of him that is included in the brochure and read the description of him as a daring escape artist, I was not interested. I thought the show would be focused on escapes, which I really don’t enjoy (also, I thought the photo gave kind of a dark impression of both him and the show—not appealing to me). I bought the tickets later not realizing this was the same show I’d read about earlier, and regretted it. But we went anyway, so as not to waste the money spent, and happily it was more focused on other kinds of magic than on escapes, so we enjoyed it. However, I don’t think we’d be interested in seeing another magic show in the next year at least.
